```javascript
function printPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
  // Check if the input is an array of 5 numbers
  if (!Array.isArray(numbers) || numbers.length !== 5) {
    console.log("Please provide an array of exactly 5 numbers.");
    return;
  }

  // Function to check if a number is prime
  function isPrime(number) {
    // Check if number is less than 2 or not an integer
    if (number < 2 || !Number.isInteger(number)) {
      return false;
    }
    // Check divisibility by numbers less than itself
    for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(number); i++) {
      if (number % i === 0) {
        return false;
      }
    }
    return true;
  }

  // Iterate over the array and print prime numbers
  numbers.forEach(number => {
    if (isPrime(number)) {
      console.log(number);
    }
  });
}

// Example usage
printPrimeNumbers([3, 5, 8, 13, 21]);
```

This function first checks if the input is exactly an array of 5 numbers. Then, it defines an `isPrime` function that determines if a given number is prime. It does so by checking if the number is less than 2 or not an integer (since prime numbers are greater than 1 and are integers), and then checks for divisibility by any number from 2 up to the square root of the number (an efficient way to check for factors). Finally, it iterates over the input array and uses the `isPrime` function to check each number, printing it to the console if it is prime.

Remember, prime numbers are those that have exactly two distinct positive divisors: 1 and the number itself. So, this function will print numbers that meet this criterion.

